05178nam a22007815i 9780231508964DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2003    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315089647 a10.7312/sanc127322doi  a(DE-B1597)459296  a(OCoLC)60931267  a(OCoLC)979739266  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBR1644.5.U 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a289.94089680731 aWalsh, Arlene Sánchez, eauthor.10aLatino Pentecostal Identity :bEvangelical Faith, Self, and Society /cArlene Sánchez Walsh. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource :b13 illus., 5 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aReligion and American Culture00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. El Aposento Alto -- t2. Workers for the Harvest: LABI and the Institutionalizing of a Latino Pentecostal Identity -- t3. "Normal Church Can't Take Us": Victory Outreach and the Re-Creation of a Latino Pentecostal Identity -- t4. Slipping Into Darkness: "God's Anointed Now Generation" and the Making of a Latino Evangelical Youth Culture -- t5. Worlds Apart: The Vineyard, La Viña, and the American Evangelical Subculture -- tEpilogue -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOf the thirty-seven million Latinos living in the United States, nearly five million declare themselves to be either Pentecostal or Charismatic, and more convert every day. Latino Pentecostal Identity examines the historical and contemporary rise of Pentecostalism among Latinos, their conversion from other denominations, and the difficulties involved in reconciling conflicts of ethnic and religious identity. The book also looks at how evangelical groups encourage the severing of ethnic ties in favor of spiritual community and the ambivalence Latinos face when their faith fails to protect them from racial discrimination. Latinos are not new to Pentecostalism; indeed, they have been becoming Pentecostal for more than a hundred years. Thus several generations have never belonged to any other faith. Yet, as Arlene M. Sánchez Walsh articulates, the perception of adherents as Catholic converts persists, eliding the reality of a specific Latino Pentecostal population that both participates in the spiritual and material culture of the larger evangelical Christian movement and imprints that movement with its own experiences. Focusing on three groups of Latino Pentecostals/Charismatics-the Assemblies of God, Victory Outreach, and the Vineyard-Sánchez Walsh considers issues such as the commodification of Latino evangelical culture, the Latinization of Pentecostalism, and the ways in which Latino Pentecostals have differentiated themselves from the larger Latino Catholic culture. Extensive fieldwork, surveys, and personal interviews inform her research and show how, in an overwhelmingly Euro-American denomination, diverse Latino faith communities-U.S. Chicano churches, pan-Latin American immigrant churches, and mixed Latin American and U.S. Latino churches-have carved out their own unique religious space.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aHispanic American Pentecostals. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066254208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045952440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/sanc12732423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231508964.jpg  a978-3-11-044247-2  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013  a978-3-11